'''Bayou virus (BAYV)''' is a species of [[hantavirus]] first identified in 1994 in Louisiana.<ref name=louis1 >{{Cite journal | last1 = Morzunov | first1 = S. P. | last2 = Feldmann | first2 = H. | last3 = Spiropoulou | first3 = C. F. | last4 = Semenova | first4 = V. A. | last5 = Rollin | first5 = P. E. | last6 = Ksiazek | first6 = T. G. | last7 = Peters | first7 = C. J. | last8 = Nichol | first8 = S. T. | title = A newly recognized virus associated with a fatal case of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome in Louisiana | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 69 | issue = 3 | pages = 1980–1983 | year = 1995 | pmid = 7853545 | pmc = 188821}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1002/jmv.1890460320 | last1 = Khan | first1 = A. S. | last2 = Spiropoulou | first2 = C. F. | last3 = Morzunov | first3 = S. | last4 = Zaki | first4 = S. R. | last5 = Kohn | first5 = M. A. | last6 = Nawas | first6 = S. R. | last7 = McFarland | first7 = L. | last8 = Nichol | first8 = S. T. | title = Fatal illness associated with a new hantavirus in Louisiana | journal = Journal of medical virology | volume = 46 | issue = 3 | pages = 281–286 | year = 1995 | pmid = 7561804}}</ref> In 1996, the [[marsh rice rat]] was identified as the [[natural reservoir]] of the virus,<ref name=ricerat >{{Cite journal | last1 = Ksiazek | first1 = T. G. | last2 = Nichol | first2 = S. T. | last3 = Mills | first3 = J. N. | last4 = Groves | first4 = M. G. | last5 = Wozniak | first5 = A. | last6 = McAdams | first6 = S. | last7 = Monroe | first7 = M. C. | last8 = Johnson | first8 = A. M. | last9 = Martin | first9 = M. L. | last10 = Peters | first10 = C. J. | last11 = Rollin | first11 = P. E. | title = Isolation, genetic diversity, and geographic distribution of Bayou virus (Bunyaviridae: Hantavirus) | journal = The American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene | volume = 57 | issue = 4 | pages = 445–448 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9347961}}</ref>
indicating the virus to be widespread throughout the [[Southeastern United States]].<ref name=socioeco >{{Cite journal | last1 = Holsomback | first1 = T. S. | last2 = Van Nice | first2 = C. J. | last3 = Clark | first3 = R. N. | last4 = McIntyre | first4 = N. E. | last5 = Abuzeineh | first5 = A. A. | last6 = Salazar-Bravo | first6 = J. | title = Socio-ecology of the marsh rice rat (Oryzomys palustris) and the spatio-temporal distribution of Bayou virus in coastal Texas | journal = Geospatial health | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 289–298 | year = 2013 | pmid = 23733291 | doi=10.4081/gh.2013.87}}</ref> BAYV infection causes [[hantavirus pulmonary syndrome]] (HPS) and represents the second most common hantavirus in the [[United States]] behind the [[Sin Nombre virus]].<ref name=secondus >{{Cite journal | last1 = Holsomback | first1 = T. S. | last2 = McIntyre | first2 = N. E. | last3 = Nisbett | first3 = R. A. | last4 = Strauss | first4 = R. E. | last5 = Chu | first5 = Y. K. | last6 = Abuzeineh | first6 = A. A. | last7 = De La Sancha | first7 = N. | last8 = Dick | first8 = C. W. | last9 = Jonsson | first9 = C. B. | doi = 10.1111/j.1948-7134.2009.00003.x | last10 = Morris | first10 = B. E. L. | title = Bayou virus detected in non-oryzomyine rodent hosts: An assessment of habitat composition, reservoir community structure, and marsh rice rat social dynamics | journal = Journal of Vector Ecology | volume = 34 | issue = 1 | pages = 9–21 | year = 2009 | pmid = 20836801 | pmc = }}</ref>

