{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = Small Is Profitable | title_orig = | translator = | image = Small is Profitable.jpg | caption = | author = [[Amory Lovins]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = | publisher = | release_date = [[2002 in literature|2002]] | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = | dewey = | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Small Is Profitable: The Hidden Economic Benefits of Making Electrical Resources the Right Size''''' is a 2002 book by energy analyst [[Amory Lovins]] and others. The book describes 207 ways in which the size of "electrical resources"—devices that make, save, or store electricity—affects their economic value. It finds that properly accounting for the economic benefits of "distributed" (decentralized) electrical resources typically raises their value by a large factor, perhaps tenfold, through improved system planning, utility construction and operation (especially off the grid), and service quality, and by avoiding [[social cost]]s. This should change how [[renewable energy|distributed resource]]s are marketed and used, and make policy and business opportunities explicit.<ref name=small> [http://www.smallisprofitable.org/ Small Is profitable]</ref>
''Small Is Profitable'' was named 'Book of the Year' by ''[[The Economist]]'' magazine.<ref name=small/><ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-96498435.html 'Small Is Profitable' Named 'Book of the Year' by The Economist; Book Brings New Thinking to Electricity Industry]</ref>{{citation needed|reason = Those links appear not to be credible, they don't actually point to the Economist, they point to self referential material |date = November 2015}}
